The Painganga Wildlife Sanctuary, located in the Indian state of Maharashtra, is a protected forest area situated on both sides of the Painganga River, which serves as a natural boundary between the Yavatmal and Nanded districts. Established on January 1, 1996, it spans an area of approximately 325 square kilometers, primarily within the Pusad forest division. The sanctuary is known for its dry deciduous forest ecosystem, with teak as the predominant tree species. 
The sanctuary is surrounded on three sides by water, which contributes to the diverse flora supported by an average annual rainfall between 1000 mm and 1500 mm, according to Wikipedia. Among the trees found here are Arjun, Amla, Kadamba, Gulvel, Charoli, Tamarind, Dhavda, Behda, Moha, and Haldu. The sanctuary also boasts approximately 200 species of herbs, along with various reeds and grasses such as Kusali, Khas, Tirkadi, Pavanya, and Marvel. 
The sanctuary is home to a variety of animals, including herbivores like pangolins, chinkara, chital, four-horned antelope, nilgai, and Indian muntjac. Smaller carnivores such as striped hyenas and jungle cats are present, along with larger ones like leopards and wild dogs. Numerous reptile and bird species also inhabit the area. 
