            <h2>Yavatmal Fort (Pohara Hill)</h2>







<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >

            <p> 

                

Based on the available information, Yavatmal Fort, also known as Pohara Hill, is a historical fortification located in the Yavatmal district of Maharashtra, India. 
It is believed to have been constructed by the Gond kings in the 12th century. 
The fort is built on a spur of the Sahyadri Mountains and is surrounded by dense forests. It stands at an approximate elevation of 3,543 feet (1,080 meters) above sea level. While now in ruins, it still offers panoramic views of the city. The Department of Tourism Maharashtra website mentions the fort has a number of bastions and was once well-defended. 
Over the centuries, Yavatmal, including the fort, witnessed the rule of various empires and regional powers, including the Bahmani Sultanate, the Ahmednagar Sultanate, and the Mughal Empire. It later came under Maratha and then British control. 
The fort's current condition is described as being in ruins. Efforts towards conservation of forts in Maharashtra are underway, and the state government has schemes for preservation, repair, and conservation work, including preparing district-wise gazetteers and promoting cultural tourism related to forts. 
