        <section id="Mahur (Renuka Devi Temple)" class="section">
            <h2>Mahur (Renuka Devi Temple)</h2>









<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >

<p>


Mahur's Shri Renuka Mata Shakti Peeth Mandir is a revered temple situated atop a hill in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, India, and considered one of the three and a half Shakti Peethas in the state. Dedicated to Goddess Renuka, the mother of Lord Parashurama (an incarnation of Lord Vishnu), this temple holds immense significance for devotees and is mentioned in ancient scriptures like Devi Gita as the abode of Devi Renuka in the Sahyadri mountains. Legend has it that Renuka's head fell here after being beheaded by her son Parashurama at the command of his father, Sage Jamadagni, making the site a sacred spot where the presence of Shakti is believed to reside. The present temple, showcasing intricate architecture including carved stone walls and grand pillars, is believed to have been built by a Yadava king of Devagiri centuries ago. Visitors ascend approximately 200-250 steps to reach the temple, surrounded by scenic beauty and dense forests, and can also find nearby shrines dedicated to Lord Parashurama and Lord Dattatreya. A major fair is held annually during the Dasara festival (also known as Dussehra) to honor Renuka Devi, attracting thousands of devotees. 




</p>
