        <section id="Kalamb Shri Chintamani Ganesh Mandir" class="section">
            <h2>Kalamb Shri Chintamani Ganesh Mandir</h2>






<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >


            <p> 



                The Shri Chintamani Ganesh Mandir in Kalamb is a unique underground temple dedicated to Lord Ganesha, nestled in the Vidarbha region of Maharashtra, about 20-22 km from Yavatmal city. Constructed between the 7th and 8th centuries, it holds significance as one of the 21 Kshetras (pilgrimage sites) of Ganapati in Maharashtra and one of the eight revered Ganapati Kshetras in Vidarbha, also known as Vidarbha Ashtavinayak. The temple's unique feature is its subterranean location, situated 27-30 feet below ground level, requiring visitors to descend steps to reach the sanctum-sanctorum. 
The legend surrounding the temple describes how Lord Ganesha blessed Lord Indra at this very site, relieving him of a curse incurred from Rishi Gautam, who had been wronged by Indra's deception. Indra's Guru, Bruhaspati, also surrendered alongside Indra to seek forgiveness from Sage Gautam. Maharshi Gautam instructed Indra to chant the Ganesh Mantra and perform austerities to appease Shri Chintamani in the Kalamb region. Pleased with Indra's penance, Lord Ganesha manifested and, using his goad, created a pond, the Ganesh Kund, from which Indra bathed and was cured. A unique feature of this temple is that the main idol, a 4.5 feet high Lord Ganesha, is dakshinabhimukh, meaning it faces south. This orientation is said to be because Ganesha appeared before Indra, who was performing austerities facing south. 
The temple is also known for a periodic phenomenon where, once every 12 years in the Hindu month of Ashwin (Sept-Oct), the water from the Ganesh Kund rises and partially submerges the idol. This is believed to be a testament to King Indra having first brought the holy Ganga to this location for the worship of Shri Chintamani. The Chintamani Yatra commences on the Magh Shukla Paksha Pratipada, drawing thousands of devotees. Fairs and events are organized from Chaturthi to Saptami, with Ganesh Chaturthi and Durga Puja being particularly popular. Visitors are welcomed year-round, with the peak season being during festivals like Ganesh Chaturthi and Sankashti Chaturthi, and the winter months (September to February) being the most pleasant. The temple is well-maintained and provides a serene and spiritual environment for devotees seeking peace and blessings from Lord Ganesha. 
