        <section id="Sahastrakund Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Sahastrakund Waterfall</h2>


            
           



<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,">
            <p>  
      

ahastrakund Waterfall, also known as Sahastrakunda or Penganga Waterfall, is a picturesque waterfall situated on the Painganga River in the Nanded district of Maharashtra, India. The waterfall is nestled on the border of the Nanded and Yavatmal districts, showcasing the natural beauty of the region. The name "Sahastrakund" translates to "thousand ponds," a fitting description for the numerous small pools and cascades formed by the water as it plunges down from a height of 50 feet. The unique rock formations surrounding the waterfall, resembling dark metallic structures, add to its geological appeal. 
Beyond its natural beauty, Sahastrakund holds cultural and historical significance, with ancient temples in the area like the Panchamukhi Mahadev Temple, Ram Temple, and Banganga Mahadev Temple. The surrounding forests are home to diverse flora and fauna, making it an appealing spot for nature enthusiasts. 

</p>

        </section>

        <section id="Yelabara Waterfall" class="section">
            <h2>Yelabara Waterfall</h2>


            
           


<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >

<p>


Yelabara Waterfall, located in the Yavatmal District of Maharashtra, is a popular tourist attraction known for its beautiful cascade and lush surroundings. Situated approximately 30-50 kilometers from Yavatmal City, it is considered an ideal destination for a one-day trip with family and friends. The journey to the waterfall includes a short trek along a scenic river and through a jungle trail. Although the approach road can be narrow and unpaved in some sections, requiring a walk of about 750 meters by the riverside to reach the falls, the experience is considered rewarding. 
The Yelabara Waterfall area features two impressive waterfalls and a large dam with a reservoir, resembling a jungle and offering a minor trekking experience amidst unique stone formations. While enjoying the natural beauty, it is advised to be cautious, especially with children, due to the high water flow and the depth of the waterfalls. Swimming is not recommended, and visitors should stay away from the water due to potential hazards like strong currents and deep sections. 


</p>
   
        </section>

        <section id="Prerna Sthal" class="section">
            <h2>Prerna Sthal</h2>



            


           

<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64," >

            <p>


The Prerna Sthal is a new area within the Parliament House Complex where statues of India's prominent leaders and freedom fighters have been relocated from various parts of the complex. Vice President Shri Jagdeep Dhankhar inaugurated the Prerna Sthal, hoping it would inspire visitors with the stories and legacies of these leaders. The project aims to improve visitor access to the statues and use QR codes to share the life stories of these figures. The relocation drew criticism from the Opposition, who called it a unilateral decision that violated democratic traditions, especially regarding the statues of Mahatma Gandhi and Dr. B.R. Ambedkar, which were moved from their original, prominent spots used for protests. The Prerna Sthal was inaugurated with the stated goal of bringing these figures together to preserve their legacy and inspire future generations. 



            </p>
</section>

