        <section id="Nilona Dam" class="section">
            <h2>Nilona Dam</h2>







<img src="data:image/jpeg;base64,">


 <p>  
    




    Nilona Dam, located approximately 14 kilometers from Yavatmal in Maharashtra, India, is an earth-fill dam that serves as a primary source of drinking water for the residents of Yavatmal and surrounding areas. The dam is part of an irrigation project undertaken by the Maharashtra government. 
Constructed in 1972, the reservoir originally had a capacity of 6.39 million cubic meters. However, due to siltation over time, its capacity has been reduced by an estimated one-third, according to government data. Local activists suggest the reduction could be as much as half due to the combined effect of silt and vegetation. 
In 2015, a citizen-led initiative called "Mission Deep Nilona" (MDN), spearheaded by the Prayas network of professionals, embarked on a crowd-funded project to de-silt the reservoir. MDN raised 2.3 million rupees from private donations and secured the remaining funds and necessary approvals from the government for the estimated 3.5 million rupee project. The initiative also received donations of equipment like dredgers and trucks, as well as volunteer labor from approximately 12,000 people. Beyond restoring the reservoir's capacity, the project aimed to utilize the removed silt as a natural fertilizer to improve agricultural yields in the region, which has been severely affected by drought. 
Despite the challenging, rocky road leading to the dam, it's considered a beautiful natural site, particularly popular during the monsoon season. Visitors to Nilona Dam can enjoy scenic views and a tranquil environment. It's a popular spot for picnics and day outings. However, there are no commercial facilities on site, so visitors are advised to bring their own food and water. The best views of the reservoir are reportedly available from the village of Godhani. 
